data: {"index":0,"blockType":"text","finalContent":"---\n\n## Cross-Cloud Cost Analysis — Full Results Report\n\n### Executive Summary\n\n**All 9 tool calls failed.** The MCP proxy backend is returning `HTTP 500 — Internal error: \"Attempt to overwrite 'args' in LogRecord\"` across every cloud connector. This is a **new error signature** compared to the previous `ECONNREFUSED` failures — the proxy is reachable but crashing internally due to a **Python logging framework bug**.\n\n---\n\n## Tool Execution Results\n\n| # | Tool | Cloud | Purpose | Status | Error |\n|:-:|------|:-----:|---------|:------:|-------|\n| 1 | `aws_identity` | AWS | Account identity | ❌ | HTTP 500 — LogRecord overwrite |\n| 2 | `aws_cost_summary` | AWS | MTD total spend | ❌ | HTTP 500 — LogRecord overwrite |\n| 3 | `aws_cost_by_service` | AWS | Service breakdown | ❌ | HTTP 500 — LogRecord overwrite |\n| 4 | `azure_list_subscriptions` | Azure | Subscription inventory | ❌ | HTTP 500 — LogRecord overwrite |\n| 5 | `azure_cost_query` | Azure | MTD cost query | ❌ | HTTP 500 — LogRecord overwrite |\n| 6 | `azure_cost_by_service` | Azure | Service breakdown | ❌ | HTTP 500 — LogRecord overwrite |\n| 7 | `call_aws` (STS fallback) | AWS | Direct CLI fallback | ❌ | HTTP 500 — LogRecord overwrite |\n| 8 | `call_aws` (CE fallback) | AWS | Direct Cost Explorer | ❌ | HTTP 500 — LogRecord overwrite |\n| 9 | `azure_arm_execute` (fallback) | Azure | Direct ARM REST | ❌ | HTTP 500 — LogRecord overwrite |\n| 10 | `k8s_cluster_health` | K8s | Platform diagnostic | ❌ | No kubeconfig found |\n\n---\n\n## Root Cause Analysis\n\n### New Error vs. Previous Outages\n\n| Audit | Error Signature | Proxy State |\n|:-----:|-----------------|:-----------:|\n| Audits 1–3 | `ECONNREFUSED 10.43.224.106:8080` | Pod down / crashed |\n| Audit 4 (previous) | `ECONNREFUSED 10.43.224.106:8080` | Total outage |\n| **Audit 5 (now)** | **`HTTP 500: Attempt to overwrite 'args' in LogRecord`** | **Running but broken** |\n\n### Diagnosis\n\nThe error `\"Attempt to overwrite 'args' in LogRecord\"` is a **known Python `logging` module issue** that occurs when:\n\n1. **A custom log formatter or handler** attempts to set `args` on a `LogRecord` object that already has it populated — this is disallowed in Python 3.12+\n2. **Concurrent log writes** from multiple async tool handlers create a race condition on shared `LogRecord` instances\n3. **A library upgrade** (e.g., `structlog`, `python-json-logger`, or the `logging` stdlib itself) introduced stricter immutability checks\n\n> [!IMPORTANT]\n> The proxy **is running** (it responds with HTTP 500 instead of ECONNREFUSED), but it crashes on **every request** before reaching any cloud API. This is a code-level bug, not an infrastructure outage.\n\n---\n\n## Remediation\n\n| Priority | Action | Rationale |\n|:--------:|--------|-----------|\n| **P0** | **Collect proxy logs** — `kubectl logs -n openagentic -l app=openagentic-mcp-proxy --tail=200` | Capture the full Python traceback to identify the exact log handler and line |\n| **P0** | **Hotfix the logging code** — look for `record.args = ...` in custom formatters and replace with `LogRecord` factory pattern or `extra={}` | Direct fix for the crash. Common culprits: JSON log formatters, correlation-ID middleware |\n| **P0** | **Restart with rollback** — `kubectl rollout undo deployment/openagentic-mcp-proxy -n openagentic` | If a recent deployment introduced the bug, rollback to the last working image |\n| **P1** | **Pin Python logging dependencies** — ensure `python-json-logger`, `structlog`, or equivalent are pinned to compatible versions | Prevents recurrence from transitive dependency upgrades |\n| **P1** | **Add error-handling middleware** — wrap all MCP tool dispatch in `try/except` so logging failures don't crash the request | Logging bugs should degrade to missing logs, not HTTP 500s |\n| **P1** | **Add health check with synthetic tool call** — liveness probe that executes a lightweight tool (e.g., `list_subscriptions`) end-to-end | Current health check likely only checks HTTP listener, not actual tool execution path |\n\n---\n\n## Incident Timeline (Cumulative)\n\n```mermaid\ntimeline\n    title MCP Proxy Reliability — 5 Consecutive Failures\n    section Audits 1-3\n        Partial Outage : AWS/Azure ✅, Admin/K8s ❌\n                       : ECONNREFUSED on admin subsystem\n    section Audit 4\n        Total Outage : All tools ❌\n                     : ECONNREFUSED across all connectors\n    section Audit 5 (Current)\n        Running but Broken : All tools ❌\n                           : HTTP 500 Python LogRecord bug\n                           : New error class — code defect, not infra\n```\n\n---\n\n## Recommendation\n\nThis is **no longer an infrastructure stability problem** — it is a **software defect** in the MCP proxy's logging layer. The immediate path is:\n\n1. **Pull the pod logs** to get the full traceback\n2. **Rollback the deployment** if a recent change caused it\n3. **Fix the logging code** (likely a one-line fix in a custom formatter)\n4. **Re-run this cost analysis** once the proxy is healthy\n\nOnce the proxy is restored, I will immediately re-execute all 6 cost queries and deliver the full cross-cloud financial report. Would you like me to attempt any alternative data-gathering approach in the meantime (e.g., web search for your AWS/Azure billing console URLs)?"}

